        title: "Wrap up the day so you can live with more meaning",
        text: "How many nights have you counted sheep because of a stubborn thought that would not let go. Maybe you were plotting tomorrow or replaying a chat at the water cooler. Mornings need rhythm, and so do evenings. The last thought before sleep tends to be the first one when you wake, so the closing slice of therapy should become your bedtime ritual.\n\nJot down the day's snag and let it drift away. Catch the stressful beats on the page in this way. Recall and describe the moment as plainly as possible, sticking to the facts. Write down your read of the moment. Note how that read shaped your reaction, your thoughts, and your behavior. Sum up the dark patterns you spotted. Swap them for kinder alternatives and let the whole experience go. If you need to, close the eyes and picture the problem floating away, with no grip on you.\n\nA bright morning is planted in a soft evening.\n\nHunt for the day's lesson. This slice is about catching a moment, maybe a line your friend tossed out or a chain of thoughts sparked by a scene in a book, that made you think or feel something fresh. Ask what it can hand you. You may suddenly notice that your partner cares about you, or that you need more rest. These nudges feel small, but they are rich fuel for a better life.\n\nWash, recharge, and seal the day. Grab a bowl and dip your hands in it. As you wash, picture the hardships, pain, and struggles running off with the water. The ritual resets the mind, and in many traditions it is a sacred gesture that soothes body and soul. Touch something bigger than yourself. It can be God, the universe, or any spirit you trust. You do not have to be religious. Look up at the sky and see how small your problem looks beside the infinite dark. Meditation, prayer, or other spiritual practices are powerful tools for keeping mental peace, resilience, and hope when times get hard. Tip your hat to the day and quiet the mind. Let the silence settle and steady you. You are ready to call it a night. The chair holds you one more hour, then the pillow waits. A calm end is a small gift you can hand yourself every evening, and a steady ritual trains the mind to land gently on the pillow."
